== Rivalries ==

Turkey has developed several notable rivalries, the most well-known being [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://apnews.com/24dbb8d918284353a71c83db96f89d23|title=Croatia and Turkey resume old European rivalry in Paris|work=AP News|access-date=2 July 2018|archive-date=2 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702064431/https://apnews.com/24dbb8d918284353a71c83db96f89d23|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Greece national football team|Greece]].

Turkey and Croatia have played each other nine times,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.11v11.com/teams/croatia/tab/opposingTeams/opposition/Turkey/|title=Croatia national football team: record v Turkey|website=www.11v11.com|access-date=2 July 2018|archive-date=2 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702011259/https://www.11v11.com/teams/croatia/tab/opposingTeams/opposition/Turkey/|url-status=live}}</ref> with their first encounter at [[UEFA Euro 1996|Euro 1996]]; where both countries made their debuts in the opening match, which Croatia won 1–0.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/history/news/0254-0d7b32db832e-4e47db7d7ee0-1000--croatia-leave-it-late-against-turkey-in-euro-96-group-d/|title=UEFA EURO 1996 - History - Turkey-Croatia|date=2003-10-06|work=[[UEFA]]|access-date=2 July 2018|archive-date=3 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703183120/https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1996/matches/round=227/match=52513/postmatch/report/index.html|url-status=live}}</ref> In [[UEFA Euro 2008|Euro 2008]], Turkey won on penalties after a 1–1 deadlock. The two teams faced each other in the [[UEFA Euro 2012 qualifying|2012 Euro qualifying play-offs]], with Croatia winning 3–0 in the first-leg in [[Istanbul]], and advancing to the tournament finals following a 0–0 draw in the second-leg.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/history/news/0254-0d7d23e88abc-9c0c36676205-1000--croatia-build-big-lead-in-turkey/|title=UEFA EURO 2012 - History - Turkey-Croatia|date=2011-11-11|work=[[UEFA]]|access-date=2 July 2018|archive-date=15 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715111454/https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2012/matches/round=2000113/match=2008824/postmatch/report/index.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/match/2008828--croatia-vs-turkiye/|title=UEFA EURO 2012 - History - Croatia-Turkey |date=2011-11-15|work=[[UEFA]]|access-date=2 July 2018|archive-date=3 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703183116/https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2012/matches/round=2000113/match=2008828/index.html|url-status=live}}</ref> The two teams faced each other once again in a European competition at [[UEFA Euro 2016|Euro 2016]], playing in the opening match of [[UEFA Euro 2016#Group D|Group D]], with Croatia winning 1–0.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/36454287|title=Turkey 0-1 Croatia|date=12 June 2016|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2 July 2018|archive-date=9 June 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230609194511/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/36454287|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://sport.hrt.hr/339010/euro2016/euro-2016-hrvatska-turska|title=[VIDEO] Modrić golčinom srušio žestoke Turke!|work=Hrvatska radiotelevizija|access-date=2 July 2018|archive-date=2 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702065816/http://sport.hrt.hr/339010/euro2016/euro-2016-hrvatska-turska|url-status=live}}</ref> Only three months after the Euros, the two teams played in their opening match in [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group I|Group I of 2018 FIFA World Cup qualifying]], which finished 1–1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/round=276483/match=300332124/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924231753/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/round=276483/match=300332124/index.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=24 September 2015|title=2018 FIFA World Cup Russia - Matches - Croatia-Turkey|website=FIFA|access-date=2 July 2018}}</ref> Exactly one year later, Turkey won the reverse fixture 1–0 at home, which played a key part in both countries' qualifying campaigns, although Turkey would not qualify for the World Cup while Croatia would finish runners-up behind France.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/round=276483/match=300332110/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924231731/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/round=276483/match=300332110/index.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=24 September 2015|title=2018 FIFA World Cup Russia - Matches - Turkey-Croatia|website=FIFA |access-date=2 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://sport.hrt.hr/403766/hrvatska-u-turskoj-trazi-vazne-bodove-za-plasman-na-sp-2035-hrt1|title=[VIDEO] Hrvatska izgubila u Eskisehiru, Turci slavili 1:0|work=Hrvatska radiotelevizija|access-date=2 July 2018|archive-date=2 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702065755/http://sport.hrt.hr/403766/hrvatska-u-turskoj-trazi-vazne-bodove-za-plasman-na-sp-2035-hrt1|url-status=live}}</ref> Turkey and Croatia would again face each other during the [[UEFA Euro 2024 qualifying]] campaign, where Turkey managed to shock Croatia with a 1–0 win away as the Turks managed to top the table of a qualification group for the first time in their history, whereas Croatia, despite a 2–0 away win earlier to Turkey, had struggled with a rather poor performance and only managed to qualify at the last hurdle.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-03-28 |title=Croatia Defeat Turkey 2-0 With Brace From Kovačić, Amazing Display From Livaković |url=https://croatiansports.com/croatia-0-turkey-0-245pm-et-kickoff-is-this-a-must-win-game/ |access-date=2024-06-13 |website=CROATIANSPORTS.COM |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=2023-11-21 |title=Croatia 1-0 Armenia: Hosts secure final automatic Euro 2024 spot with Ante Budimir goal |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/67411399 |access-date=2024-06-13 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

Turkey also has a historical rivalry with Greece. Playing 13 times, Turkey won eight matches, drew thrice, and lost only three games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.11v11.com/teams/turkey/tab/opposingTeams/opposition/Greece/|title=Turkey national football team: record v Greece|website=www.11v11.com|access-date=2 July 2018|archive-date=2 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702064434/https://www.11v11.com/teams/turkey/tab/opposingTeams/opposition/Greece/|url-status=live}}</ref> Both countries have been described as "punching above their weight", with Greece winning [[UEFA Euro 2004|Euro 2004]] after being classified as underdogs before the competition, and Turkey advancing to the semi-finals of [[UEFA Euro 2008|Euro 2008]], where they were knocked out by [[Germany national football team|Germany]]. Due to tension between the two countries and the dispute over [[Cyprus]], coupled with several incidents occurring during matches between Turkish and Greek clubs, it has been described as one of the biggest international football rivalries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/SPORT/football/11/06/first11.rivalries/index.html|title=Top 10 international rivalries|first=Greg|last=Duke|website=CNN|access-date=2 July 2018|archive-date=20 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200220051229/http://edition.cnn.com/2008/SPORT/football/11/06/first11.rivalries/index.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

